            <a:r>
              <a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/>
              <a:t>Picture uploading a contract with 'Clause 3.2: Indemnification' and 'Clause 10: Termination'. Old approach? Split at character boundaries and lose structure. New approach: detect the clause headers via regex, split only at those boundaries. Each chunk gets tagged with chunk_type (clause, requirement, section, etc.) and clause_number. These tags live in PostgreSQL. This unlocks qualitatively different retrieval: instead of 'find chunks semantically similar to indemnification', you can call extract_clauses('clause 3.2') and get the exact text. The requirement detector catches 'shall', 'must', and 'REQ-001' style requirements, enabling get_requirement_chunks() for compliance checking and contract analysis. That's critical for the domain.</a:t>
            </a:r>
          </a:p>
        </p:txBody>
